<span class="comment"><font color=#000000>People who can't build excellent software have written many good books.<p>Writing a good tech book requires deep understanding of a subject.<p>Writing good software takes discipline, creativity, and (interestingly) not necessarily a particularly deep analytical understanding of underlying concepts. People have written truly excellent software on poor CS foundations.</font></span><p><font size=1><font color=#f6f6ef>-----</font></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table border=0><tr><td><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/s.gif" height=1 width=0></td><td valign=top><center><a id=up_3437662 href="vote?for=3437662&dir=up&whence=%2f%78%3f%66%6e%69%64%3d%73%69%73%53%73%51%37%36%58%73"><img src="http://ycombinator.com/images/grayarrow.gif" border=0 vspace=3 hspace=2></a><span id=down_3437662></span></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px; "><span class="comhead"><a href="user?id=tptacek">tptacek</a> 28 days ago  | <a href="item?id=3437662">link</a> | <a href="item?id=3437552">parent</a> | on: <a href="item?id=3437233">Ask HN: Do startups hire 50+ year old programmers?...</a></span></div><br>
